# [STIR](../wg/stir.html)

## Summary

The STIR working group met at IETF 126 to discuss the proposed Charter Version 3 and the Vesper profile documents. The group reached a general understanding on the charter text, emphasizing that the scope remains anchored to the authority model of RFC 8226 while allowing for future alternative technical mechanisms. The technical discussion primarily focused on the Vesper profile, specifically the security properties of binding telephone numbers (TNs) to domains, the architectural placement of dynamic TN attributes, and out-of-band discovery. Lastly, the ACME working group chair requested STIR community feedback to progress a critical dependency draft currently in ACME working group last call.

---

## Key Discussion Points

### 1. STIR Charter Version 3
The working group reviewed the status of the rechartering effort, focusing on proposed text for Charter Version 3 (referenced in the [Chair Introduction](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-stir-chair-introduction-00) slide deck).

*   **Scope and Authority Model:** Chris Wendt summarized list discussions regarding identifying the entity behind a call. The consensus was to exclude extending STIR to arbitrary alternative trust anchors beyond RFC 8226 certificates for the time being.
*   **Decoupling and Jurisdictions:** John Peterson emphasized that preserving the relationship between the call processing machinery (routing, subscriber assignment) and the attesting entity is critical. Decoupling assertions from administrative, regulatory, or jurisdictional frameworks would undermine the trustworthiness of first-party assertions. 
*   **Technical Flexibility:** Charles Eckel queried if the charter should limit the working group to a single entity-identification mechanism. John Peterson and Russ Housley clarified that while the current focus is on domain binding, the charter should remain flexible enough to accommodate other valid proposals (such as binding SIP URIs) if they are brought to the group.

### 2. Vesper Profile Discussion
Chris Wendt presented the current state of Vesper, as detailed in the [Vesper Profile Discussion](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-stir-vesper-profile-discussion-00) slides.

*   **Vesper as a Profile:** Vesper has evolved from an exploratory phase into a modular "profile" that acts as a guideline for combining existing STIR tools (e.g., RFC 9060 delegated certificates, short-lived certificates, Rich Call Data, and certificate transparency). 
*   **TN-by-Domain Binding:** Chris Wendt proposed binding a telephone number (TN) to a domain represented in the Subject Alternative Name (SAN) of a delegate certificate. The CA verifies domain control (using ACME) and verifies the TN (using the TN authorization list token). John Peterson supported this approach, noting that tightly binding the calling credential to the identity of the responsible entity has strong security properties.
*   **Placement of TN Attributes (DNO and Authorized Originators):** Chris Wendt proposed including self-asserted attributes, such as "Do Not Originate" (DNO) and "Authorized Originators," within the certificate structure.
    *   *Architectural Objections:* John Peterson strongly objected to baking these attributes into X.509 certificates. He argued that certificates are inherently CA-asserted rather than self-asserted. Furthermore, attributes like DNO and Authorized Originators are highly dynamic and belong in separate signed documents (signed by the holder of the private key) or within the DNS, rather than requiring certificate re-issuance.
    *   *DNO Context:* John Peterson and Eric Burger discussed how DNO is primarily enforced at the terminating side ("catcher") rather than the originating side ("pitcher"). Thus, the certificate is the wrong architectural layer for distributing this data.
    *   *Alternative Storage:* Roger Anderson suggested that once a TN is bound to a domain, the DNS could serve as a dynamic repository for these attributes. Chris Wendt agreed this was a valid path to explore.
*   **Out-of-Band & Discovery:** Chris Wendt noted that API specifications have been removed from the Vesper out-of-band draft to focus purely on discovery and connected identity. John Peterson suggested that instead of baking Call Placement Server (CPS) URLs directly into certificates, the certificate should sign an external advertisement wrapper to resolve the "chicken-and-egg" discovery problem.

### 3. ACME Coordination (JWT Claim Constraints)
Mike Ounsworth (ACME WG Chair) raised an issue regarding the *JWT Claim Constraints Profile of ACME Authority Token* draft currently sitting in ACME working group last call (WGLC). 
*   The draft has received zero responses on the ACME list since July 4, 2024. 
*   Because ACME members are unfamiliar with the STIR-specific use cases for this draft, it cannot progress without explicit support and review from STIR participants.

---

## Decisions and Action Items

*   **Charter Progression:** The working group agreed that the proposed Charter Version 3 text is ready and has been delivered to the Area Director (Charles Eckel).
*   **Adoption Strategy:** Formal adoption of the Vesper documents cannot occur until the rechartering process is officially completed. However, the sense of the room was to plan for the eventual adoption of the **Vesper Framework** and the **TN-by-Domain Binding** documents as working group items once chartered.
*   **TN Attributes Draft:** The *TN Attributes* draft will not be considered for immediate adoption; it requires more requirements-gathering and architectural refinement regarding where these attributes should reside.
*   **Action Item:** Russ Housley and Ben Campbell to send a notice to the STIR mailing list urging members to review and explicitly support the *JWT Claim Constraints Profile of ACME Authority Token* draft on the ACME working group mailing list to prevent the WGLC from failing.